    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0333"/>
        		<head>Jim to Mademoiselle Marcelle Guerin <date value="1916-05-28">May 28th [1916]</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1916-05-28">May 28th [1916]</date></dateline>
            
            <salute>Dear Marcelle:</salute>
        		</opener>
        		
            <p>
            After a long wait
            I have received the things
            necessary for repairing my
            buss and am leaving for
            Bar le Duc to morrow &mdash; weather
            permitting.
            </p><p>
            You probably know
            that Bill Thaw brought down
            a Fokker and was afterwards
            wounded in the arm.  Kiffin
            was wounded in the face
            but not badly.  Prince and
            Hall broke their machines
            to splinters.  Hope I have
     
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0335" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            better luck.  I’m going
            to pass by Toul so as
            to fly over the Bois le
            Pretre.  There should be
            some Boches around there 
            now since the Toul avion
            de chasse outfit is at 
            Verdun.
            </p><p>
            I have been stopped on
            my scheme of dropping a 
            bomb with compliments of
            Betty Baldwin.  The only
            bombs here are large ones
            but I managed to rig up
            a scheme.  I thought it was

            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0334" n="[p.3]"/>
            
            good but the others said
            it wasn’t practical.  There 
            is a Bebe here without
            a machine gun and so
            minus that weight a 10 kilo
            bomb would not be too heavy.
            I was going to let her
            drop on the square in
            Mulhouse but the Chief
            here gave me a call down
            and said that bombardments
            in this region were strictly
            forbidden until further orders.
            Taunt  bis.
            </p><p>
            I was very pleased
            to get your letter yesterday,
                      
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0336" n="[p.4]"/>
            
            and I’m glad you’re having
            an easier time at the 
            ambulance.  Sorry I’m not
            around to take up some of
            your spare minutes.
            </p><p>
            Well I must go up
            now and tell good bye to
            Rosa and Coco and then
            regulate my mitrailleuse, so
            au revoir until I get to 
            the city of confiture.
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>Yours</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim</signed>
        			
